metadata.name: Story Of Shapes #17
metadata.description:
This p5js Generative Token tells one "Story Of Shapes" 

Shapes have different meanings depending on cultures, themes, languages, countries, people, etc. 

Through these tokens, I tell you one story, the one of Teiyu Goto, Sony Designer :

In a 2010 interview with Famitsu Magazine, Goto said he was well aware that ‚Äúother game companies at the time assigned alphabet letters or colors to the buttons. We wanted something simple to remember, which is why we went with icons or symbols, and I came up with the triangle-circle-X-square combination immediately after.‚Äù A name is just a name until you impart some meaning to it.

Goto wanted to be memorable but he also wanted to make sense, at least in his own mind. ‚ÄúI gave each symbol a meaning and a color,‚Äù he states in the same interview. ‚ÄúThe triangle refers to viewpoint; I had it represent one‚Äôs head or direction and made it green. Square refers to a piece of paper; I had it represent menus or documents and made it pink. The circle and X represent ‚Äòyes‚Äô or ‚Äòno‚Äô decision-making, and I made them red and blue, respectively. People thought those colors were mixed up, and I had to reinforce to management that that‚Äôs what I wanted.‚Äù 

You understand, this is only ONE Story.

Give us YOUR Story.

St4rfcuk

By the way, You can click left button to save a .PNG file.

Features : 
- Shapes counter
- 20 Color Palettes
- Random Shapes & Colors

metadata.name: Crystalline_Orbital #42
metadata.description:
‚ÄòCrystalline_Orbital‚Äô is a variation of ‚ÄòCrystalline‚Äô‚Äîdifferent, but not different enough to warrant an initial price.

Changes from ‚ÄòCrystalline‚Äô:
- Canvas size has been reduced; the original was usually around 4000 pixels, and whilst I wanted the quality of output, it does stress the browser somewhat.
- Shapes are ellipses, rather than rectangles; one of the more obvious changes.
- Render order is randomised; the original went across from left to right, then down the canvas. This was fine with rectangles, as their change in angles was uniform and clear. With ellipses, to avoid a fish-scale effect, an order is established randomly and applied throughout.

metadata.name: Concordance #826
metadata.description:
"Concordance" is a study of color relationships in a grid structure. The sketch starts with a simple pallet. Then each color is "lerped" to get levels of transition between the colors. Each color of this newly expanded pallet walks over a grid of cells to simulate rows or columns of gradients. 

Built with p5.js 

Export to a PNG format at several different sizes.
- Press s: save the current render size
- Press t: scale to screen size
- Press f: full print size (see features for dimensions)

License: CC-BY

Please find me on Twitter and Instagram at @natenolting.

metadata.name: CR Art Sessions //2 #49
metadata.description:
Grayscale, Hold the Line, and Mondrian walk into a bar. The bartender looks up and says, "What is this, some kind of art project?"

Grayscale responds, "No, we're just here for a drink."

Hold the Line adds, "But we can definitely add some color to the place if you want."

Mondrian chimes in, "I prefer to keep things simple and stick to the basics."

The bartender shakes his head and says, "I'll be the judge of that. What can I get you all?"

Grayscale orders a Guinness, Hold the Line asks for a gin and tonic, and Mondrian asks for a glass of white wine.

The bartender serves up the drinks and says, "That will be $15.50, please."

Grayscale pulls out a twenty-dollar bill and hands it to the bartender, saying, "Keep the change."

The bartender thanks him and says, "Thanks, Grayscale. You always know how to liven up the place."

Hold the Line raises his glass and says, "Cheers to that!"

Mondrian nods and clinks glasses with the others, and the three of them enjoy their drinks and the rest of their evening at the bar.

-----

Press "e" to save a png (3240*4500 or 4500*3240 px) while in live mode.

-----

Artwork by @cristianrohr (2022)

Made with P5js and <3.

metadata.name: Con(text)ual #132
metadata.description:
Con(text)ual is a generative painting made from ASCII characters confined into shapes. Shapes are randomly drawn onto the canvas, then filled with individual characters from a character array. The density of characters is dependent upon the size of the shape, creating some transparencies and an organic feel to each shape.

I've long been interested in typography as an artform and this is an extension of my typography explorations.

There are a total of 10 color pallets. The number of shapes on each canvas varies from 3 to 9. The edition size was chosen based on the code, which lends itself well to a wide array of potential outcomes. Please get in touch with me if you want a larger resolution size for printing. 

I hope you enjoy the art!

Made with 100% Code and p5.js
Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

There is no end to these geometric patterns.
